1462
00:54:07,477 --> 00:54:09,446
Shishito peppers tend to be

1463
00:54:09,512 --> 00:54:11,881
<i>much softer and tenderer</i>
<i>than regular peppers.</i>

1464
00:54:11,948 --> 00:54:15,051
<i>And once you heat it up,</i>
<i>it becomes even softer.</i>

1465
00:54:15,118 --> 00:54:16,753
-Right.
-I see.

1466
00:54:16,820 --> 00:54:18,622
She looks very pleased.

1467
00:54:18,688 --> 00:54:21,758
-The burger enthusiast looks happy.
-This is so good.

1468
00:54:21,825 --> 00:54:23,793
And now, Chef Nam-no's Burger War King.

1469
00:54:24,127 --> 00:54:28,098
SQUID AND SHRIMP PATTY
SANDWICHED BETWEEN GRILLED SUSHI RICE

1470
00:54:28,398 --> 00:54:31,935
CHEF YOON NAM-NO'S BURGER WAR KING

1471
00:54:33,203 --> 00:54:36,373
She won't get any food
on her hands that way.

1472
00:54:36,439 --> 00:54:38,541
Did you season the seaweed too?

1473
00:54:38,608 --> 00:54:40,243
-It's just roasted seaweed.
-It is, right?

1474
00:54:40,310 --> 00:54:42,312
-I just wanted to add the aroma.
-The aroma?

1475
00:54:42,379 --> 00:54:44,714
-That's new.
-It's something new.

1476
00:54:44,781 --> 00:54:48,652
I have a feeling
this will be a hit or a miss.

1477
00:54:49,653 --> 00:54:50,687
Mmm.

1478
00:54:50,754 --> 00:54:51,788
Mmm.

1479
00:54:52,389 --> 00:54:54,190
-I wonder what that's like.
-Me too.

1480
00:54:54,257 --> 00:54:56,493
I've never had anything like this.

1481
00:54:56,559 --> 00:54:59,229
At first, it tastes like <i>gimbap</i>.

1482
00:54:59,296 --> 00:55:01,097
And then, tender shrimps

1483
00:55:01,164 --> 00:55:04,567
begin to dance around in my mouth.

1484
00:55:05,468 --> 00:55:08,672
But then the sauce balances out
the shrimps from tasting too rich.

1485
00:55:10,040 --> 00:55:11,241
What about the rice buns?

1486
00:55:11,308 --> 00:55:12,942
-It doesn't taste like rice.
-No?

1487
00:55:13,243 --> 00:55:14,210
NICE

1488
00:55:14,277 --> 00:55:17,180
I'm sure grilled rice
seasoned with sushi vinegar

1489
00:55:17,247 --> 00:55:20,383
will go nicely with shrimps,
balancing out the richness.

1490
00:55:20,450 --> 00:55:23,219
It's just unfamiliar.
She continues to go back for more.

1491
00:55:23,286 --> 00:55:25,155
THE BURGER ENTHUSIAST
IS ADDICTED TO BURGER WAR KING

1492
00:55:25,221 --> 00:55:27,724
-It's a fun flavor.
-A fun flavor?

1493
00:55:27,791 --> 00:55:30,126
Mmm. It's good.

1494
00:55:30,193 --> 00:55:31,828
Does it feel like a burger?

1495
00:55:32,829 --> 00:55:35,598
I think the perilla leaf
makes it taste like a burger.

1496
00:55:35,665 --> 00:55:37,367
-The perilla leaf?
-Unexpectedly.

1497
00:55:37,434 --> 00:55:39,002
HEHE, YIPPEE

1498
00:55:39,069 --> 00:55:40,270
I told you. It's a burger.

1499
00:55:40,337 --> 00:55:41,705
It's rarely used in burgers.

1500
00:55:41,771 --> 00:55:42,972
No, it's never used.

1501
00:55:43,039 --> 00:55:44,674
-He put in what he wanted to eat.
-I've never seen it.

1502
00:55:44,741 --> 00:55:46,409
That was a very creative choice.

1503
00:55:46,476 --> 00:55:48,111
However, it's not used for burgers

1504
00:55:48,178 --> 00:55:49,713
because it stands out.

1505
00:55:50,947 --> 00:55:52,382
It's not supposed to.

1506
00:55:52,449 --> 00:55:53,883
In actuality,

1507
00:55:53,950 --> 00:55:57,954
<i>everything he used can stand out,</i>
<i>so it could've canceled each other out.</i>

1508
00:55:58,021 --> 00:55:59,289
-I see.
-Because they're all strong?

1509
00:55:59,356 --> 00:56:00,357
Because of that.

1510
00:56:00,423 --> 00:56:03,159
It tastes different with every bite.

1511
00:56:03,226 --> 00:56:05,962
-She'd like that.
-It's one of a kind.

1512
00:56:07,163 --> 00:56:09,199
-It seems like it.
-That's new.

1513
00:56:09,265 --> 00:56:13,636
She liked it. It almost seems like
she had more of the second one.

1514
00:56:13,703 --> 00:56:16,039
They're way too different.

1515
00:56:16,106 --> 00:56:18,508
Jun-young, why don't you try it too?

1516
00:56:18,575 --> 00:56:20,877
First, 55 Guys.

1517
00:56:23,780 --> 00:56:26,216
Yes, that's how you eat a burger.

1518
00:56:26,883 --> 00:56:28,318
-I get what you mean.
-Right?

1519
00:56:28,385 --> 00:56:30,387
-Everything mixes…
-The mushroom is so good.

1520
00:56:30,987 --> 00:56:32,689
-The enoki?
-Yes.

1521
00:56:32,756 --> 00:56:35,191
The overall balance is very nice.

1522
00:56:35,258 --> 00:56:36,926
-Right?
-It's great.

1523
00:56:36,993 --> 00:56:38,628
They both mentioned the enoki.

1524
00:56:38,695 --> 00:56:40,397
That's why he keeps frying them.

1525
00:56:40,463 --> 00:56:42,499
He must've had a reason for frying them.

1526
00:56:43,500 --> 00:56:45,568
That's closer to a classic burger.

1527
00:56:45,635 --> 00:56:46,603
THE TEXTBOOK BURGER MUKBANG

1528
00:56:48,071 --> 00:56:50,173
-He eats with such gusto.
-He does.

1529
00:56:50,240 --> 00:56:52,308
-Shishito peppers.
-Shishito peppers.

1530
00:56:52,375 --> 00:56:54,377
-Deep-fried peppers.
-She said it melted away.

1531
00:56:54,444 --> 00:56:57,280
It also didn't stand out too much.
You should dip it in the sauce.

1532
00:56:57,347 --> 00:56:59,149
-Shishito pepper.
-Jun-young.

1533
00:56:59,749 --> 00:57:00,583
MMM!

1534
00:57:00,650 --> 00:57:02,185
Doesn't it melt in your mouth?

1535
00:57:03,820 --> 00:57:05,321
It goes so well together. It's so good.

1536
00:57:05,388 --> 00:57:06,723
-Does it need the sauce?
-Yes.

1537
00:57:06,790 --> 00:57:07,757
It's really…

1538
00:57:07,824 --> 00:57:09,192
JUST THE SAUCE

1539
00:57:09,692 --> 00:57:10,960
MMM

1540
00:57:11,461 --> 00:57:13,329
-The sauce is so good.
-Is it really?

1541
00:57:13,396 --> 00:57:15,265
Do you have any leftovers?

1542
00:57:16,099 --> 00:57:19,502
Next, Chef Nam-no's dish, Burger War King.

1543
00:57:22,906 --> 00:57:24,808
AMAZED

1544
00:57:24,874 --> 00:57:26,376
He makes it look delicious.

1545
00:57:26,443 --> 00:57:28,511
Doesn't it dance in your mouth?

1546
00:57:28,578 --> 00:57:30,280
-It's so good.
-Is it that good?

1547
00:57:30,914 --> 00:57:31,815
He responded immediately.

1548
00:57:31,881 --> 00:57:33,383
The sushi vinegar

1549
00:57:33,450 --> 00:57:37,187
mixes very well
with the squid and shrimp patty.

1550
00:57:38,354 --> 00:57:39,189
It looks good.

1551
00:57:39,255 --> 00:57:42,158
I personally love fried shrimp sandwiches,
so I prefer this one.

1552
00:57:42,225 --> 00:57:43,226
He likes that better.

1553
00:57:43,293 --> 00:57:44,294
Wait a second.

1554
00:57:44,928 --> 00:57:46,262
-This was her order.
-Yes.

1555
00:57:46,329 --> 00:57:49,032
He may love shrimp sandwiches,

1556
00:57:49,098 --> 00:57:51,167
but the star will come from Ye-eun.

1557
00:57:51,234 --> 00:57:52,602
This is so hard.

1558
00:57:52,669 --> 00:57:55,171
-It's now time to choose.
-It must be hard.

1559
00:57:55,238 --> 00:57:57,474
-This is really hard.
-The burger enthusiast.

1560
00:57:57,540 --> 00:58:01,177
Which one of the two will she choose?

1561
00:58:01,244 --> 00:58:04,380
<i>Press one for Nam-no's Burger War King,</i>

1562
00:58:04,447 --> 00:58:07,550
<i>and two for Hyun-suk's 55 Guys.</i>

1563
00:58:08,685 --> 00:58:09,786
Grab the remote control.

1564
00:58:09,853 --> 00:58:12,021
-I pressed it.
-You already did?

1565
00:58:12,088 --> 00:58:14,424
She pressed the button already.

1566
00:58:14,491 --> 00:58:17,193
Let's see which one Ye-eun chose. Show us!

1567
00:58:18,361 --> 00:58:21,431
-I Craved Burgers to Death.
-Isn't this too cruel?

1568
00:58:21,498 --> 00:58:24,067
They faced against each other
for the first time in this season.

1569
00:58:24,133 --> 00:58:27,370
Will it be Hyun-suk, who came back
after conquering New York?

1570
00:58:27,437 --> 00:58:30,340
Or will it be Nam-no,
who desperately wants to beat Hyun-suk?

1571
00:58:30,406 --> 00:58:32,709
Who did Ye-eun choose?

1572
00:58:33,376 --> 00:58:35,778
Whose burger did she prefer?

1573
00:58:35,845 --> 00:58:37,046
Who did she choose?

1574
00:58:38,181 --> 00:58:39,549
CHOI HYUN-SUK WINS

1575
00:58:40,049 --> 00:58:40,917
55 GUYS WINS

1576
00:58:40,984 --> 00:58:42,018
It's Choi Hyun-suk!

1577
00:58:42,085 --> 00:58:45,922
-Ye-eun chose Hyun-suk!
-It was the Burger Gramps.

1578
00:58:45,989 --> 00:58:47,457
-Yes.
-Great job.

1579
00:58:47,524 --> 00:58:51,861
Was the beef patty
a little better than the seafood one?

1580
00:58:51,928 --> 00:58:55,031
I don't mean that one was better.
They were equally delicious.

1581
00:58:55,098 --> 00:58:57,433
I always thought
adding mushrooms to a burger

1582
00:58:57,500 --> 00:59:00,637
would make it just taste like mushrooms.

1583
00:59:00,703 --> 00:59:03,706
<i>But I enjoyed this a lot, despite</i>
<i>the huge amount of mushrooms in it.</i>

1584
00:59:03,773 --> 00:59:08,077
I was amazed by his ability
to turn something I do not like

1585
00:59:08,144 --> 00:59:10,980
into something that I can enjoy.

1586
00:59:11,047 --> 00:59:13,683
This could've won
if it were served in round two.

1587
00:59:13,750 --> 00:59:15,985
-I joined the wrong round.
-You should've gone next.

1588
00:59:16,052 --> 00:59:17,320
Why did I pick this one?

1589
00:59:17,654 --> 00:59:19,188
HOW SAD…

1590
00:59:19,255 --> 00:59:22,759
Ye-eun, please put a star on Hyun-suk!

1591
00:59:23,660 --> 00:59:26,462
He begins his winning streak now

1592
00:59:26,529 --> 00:59:28,364
and takes his fifth win!

1593
00:59:28,431 --> 00:59:30,867
-Congratulations!
-Thank you.

1594
00:59:30,934 --> 00:59:33,736
Hyun-suk wins yet another star!

1595
00:59:33,803 --> 00:59:35,405
Let's take ten.

1596
00:59:35,471 --> 00:59:37,006
THE BREAK AFTER ROUND ONE

1597
00:59:37,073 --> 00:59:38,274
The burger looks great.

1598
00:59:38,341 --> 00:59:39,309
I want some.

1599
00:59:39,375 --> 00:59:40,877
-I want to try it.
-It was so good.

1600
00:59:40,944 --> 00:59:44,347
TAKES OVER THE SEAT

1601
00:59:45,682 --> 00:59:48,117
SUNG-JUN LEAVES FIRST

1602
00:59:53,423 --> 00:59:55,692
-This was so good. I mean it.
-Thank you.

1603
00:59:55,758 --> 00:59:57,827
I wanted to make
something different. It's okay.

1604
00:59:59,028 --> 01:00:00,496
You must be hungry. Haven't you eaten?

1605
01:00:00,563 --> 01:00:02,966
No, I had toast and <i>ramyeon</i>
in the green room.

1606
01:00:03,032 --> 01:00:05,501
OH…

1607
01:00:05,835 --> 01:00:07,303
MOVING ON TO THE RICE BURGER…

1608
01:00:07,370 --> 01:00:09,973
-There's some more rice here.
-What?

1609
01:00:10,039 --> 01:00:13,376
You can leave it there and go.
I'll clean everything up.

1610
01:00:13,443 --> 01:00:14,744
Okay, enjoy.

1611
01:00:16,412 --> 01:00:17,580
It's good.

1612
01:00:17,647 --> 01:00:19,983
HE EASED THE PAIN OF HIS LOSS
WITH THE BURGERS…

1613
01:00:20,049 --> 01:00:24,220
<i>This is the second round</i>
<i>with ingredients from Ye-eun's fridge.</i>

1614
01:00:24,287 --> 01:00:25,955
The new strong candidate of the show,

1615
01:00:26,022 --> 01:00:28,758
one of the young guns, Chef Kwon Sung-jun,

1616
01:00:28,825 --> 01:00:31,260
is up against the expert
in the world of bootleg cooking,

1617
01:00:31,327 --> 01:00:34,664
the old boy of the show,
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong.

1618
01:00:34,897 --> 01:00:35,732
GIGGLING

1619
01:00:35,798 --> 01:00:38,768
Both of them have been on the rise.

1620
01:00:38,835 --> 01:00:41,070
Poong is currently in second place…

1621
01:00:41,137 --> 01:00:44,173
-Second?
-…and Sung-jun has had two wins in a row.

1622
01:00:44,240 --> 01:00:46,643
-Two wins in a row?
-Chef Sung-jun is weak

1623
01:00:46,709 --> 01:00:48,678
when it comes to Gen Z.

1624
01:00:48,745 --> 01:00:52,281
I believe his win rate for Gen Z guests

1625
01:00:52,348 --> 01:00:54,050
-is 0%.
-I see.

1626
01:00:54,117 --> 01:00:55,585
-Really?
-That's the case.

1627
01:00:55,652 --> 01:00:57,186
-Idol stars?
-Only K-pop idols.

1628
01:00:57,253 --> 01:00:58,721
-All K-pop idols.
-Yes.

1629
01:00:58,788 --> 01:01:00,189
But she's not a K-pop star.

1630
01:01:00,690 --> 01:01:03,159
He recently won twice in a row,
but both times,

1631
01:01:03,226 --> 01:01:05,561
he cooked for old dudes
like Go Soo and Kangnam.

1632
01:01:05,628 --> 01:01:07,997
He must be specialized
in that kind of cooking.

1633
01:01:08,064 --> 01:01:10,133
-So that's his style.
-That's why there's that rumor.

1634
01:01:10,199 --> 01:01:11,034
What rumor?

1635
01:01:11,100 --> 01:01:14,170
-That he lied about his age.
-What?

1636
01:01:14,237 --> 01:01:15,705
That he's actually much older.

1637
01:01:15,772 --> 01:01:17,573
He's older than what he claims?

1638
01:01:17,640 --> 01:01:18,808
Nam-no, he might be older.

1639
01:01:18,875 --> 01:01:20,209
NAM-NO DOES SEEM YOUNGER

1640
01:01:20,276 --> 01:01:22,111
I was born exactly on January 1st, 1995.

1641
01:01:22,178 --> 01:01:23,713
-January 1st, 1995.
-January 1st?

1642
01:01:23,780 --> 01:01:27,250
You were born in 1998, right?
You two are closer in age.

1643
01:01:27,316 --> 01:01:28,584
I'm totally her generation.

1644
01:01:28,651 --> 01:01:30,887
Sung-jun, have you analyzed Poong?

1645
01:01:30,953 --> 01:01:32,955
One of my nicknames is Matge Liang.

1646
01:01:33,022 --> 01:01:34,023
-Matge Liang.
-Why?

1647
01:01:34,090 --> 01:01:36,025
-Like Zhuge Liang.
-I did a wonderful analysis.

1648
01:01:36,092 --> 01:01:38,161
He makes up his own nicknames.

1649
01:01:38,227 --> 01:01:39,929
I analyzed the reason

1650
01:01:39,996 --> 01:01:43,433
-why Poong has been doing well recently.
-Yes?

1651
01:01:43,499 --> 01:01:45,802
He always makes the same thing,
so naturally, he got better.

1652
01:01:45,868 --> 01:01:47,870
-That's true.
-The chili oil.

1653
01:01:47,937 --> 01:01:49,972
-He got better through practice.
-He only makes chili oil.

1654
01:01:50,039 --> 01:01:51,974
So you'll easily win against him

1655
01:01:52,041 --> 01:01:54,310
-if he doesn't make chili oil?
-He'll have no chance against me.

1656
01:01:54,377 --> 01:01:55,411
Today,

1657
01:01:55,478 --> 01:01:57,346
I am not making chili oil.

1658
01:01:57,413 --> 01:01:59,515
-He's lying.
-I won't make it.

1659
01:01:59,582 --> 01:02:01,784
Wait and see. He'll make green onion oil.

1660
01:02:01,851 --> 01:02:04,353
-I will not make any kind of oil.
-Are you serious?

1661
01:02:04,420 --> 01:02:05,488
-What?
-Are you serious?

1662
01:02:05,555 --> 01:02:09,225
-I'll show you that I can win without it.
-All right.

1663
01:02:09,292 --> 01:02:12,595
Also, he gets destroyed miserably
when he's up against Eun-yeong.

1664
01:02:12,662 --> 01:02:14,430
That means he's weak
against authentic Chinese,

1665
01:02:14,497 --> 01:02:16,199
because he's unorthodox.

1666
01:02:16,265 --> 01:02:19,102
However, I'm someone
who is licensed in Chinese cuisine,

1667
01:02:19,168 --> 01:02:20,136
which makes me orthodox.

1668
01:02:20,203 --> 01:02:23,473
-I see.
-So I'll mix in Chinese techniques

1669
01:02:23,539 --> 01:02:25,775
and show him my side
as an authentic Chinese chef.

1670
01:02:25,842 --> 01:02:28,711
Eun-yeong, do you consider him
an orthodox Chinese chef?

1671
01:02:28,778 --> 01:02:29,812
RELUCTANT…

1672
01:02:29,879 --> 01:02:31,447
A mere license

1673
01:02:31,514 --> 01:02:33,983
-isn't enough to call him that.
-Not yet?

1674
01:02:34,050 --> 01:02:36,919
-There is one thing I can guarantee.
-What is it?

1675
01:02:36,986 --> 01:02:38,588
Compared to Amy Park's Italian,

1676
01:02:38,654 --> 01:02:39,856
my Chinese is far better.

1677
01:02:39,922 --> 01:02:41,591
SPEECHLESS

1678
01:02:41,657 --> 01:02:44,527
-That's true.
-He's totally right about that.

1679
01:02:44,794 --> 01:02:47,864
CONFIRMATIONS FROM BOTH SIDES…

1680
01:02:48,698 --> 01:02:51,234
CHEF KWON SUNG-JUN'S INGREDIENTS:
BRISKET, PORK NECK, SHRIMP, TOFU,

1681
01:02:51,300 --> 01:02:53,870
FISH CAKE, PORK GUKBAP BROTH,
FROZEN DUMPLINGS, FETTUCCINE, AND MORE

1682
01:02:53,936 --> 01:02:56,239
What are you making, Chef Sung-jun?

1683
01:02:56,305 --> 01:02:57,540
The name of my dish is

1684
01:02:58,241 --> 01:02:59,776
Doctor on the Matfia.

1685
01:02:59,842 --> 01:03:01,811
-Doctor on the Matfia.
-With those gloves.

1686
01:03:01,878 --> 01:03:04,380
It's a parody of the title
of her upcoming drama.

1687
01:03:04,447 --> 01:03:05,848
Yes, <i>Doctor on the Edge.</i>

1688
01:03:05,915 --> 01:03:07,150
What I'm going to make

1689
01:03:07,216 --> 01:03:09,318
is <i>gimbap</i> using pasta.

1690
01:03:09,385 --> 01:03:10,887
<i>Gimbap</i> using pasta?

1691
01:03:10,953 --> 01:03:14,290
I'll make pasta
that tastes like dandan noodles.

1692
01:03:14,357 --> 01:03:16,325
-What?
-I'll use a variety of ingredients

1693
01:03:16,392 --> 01:03:19,128
to add different textures,
flavors, and aromas.

1694
01:03:19,195 --> 01:03:22,231
She ordered
A New Dish That'll Surpass Burgers,

1695
01:03:22,298 --> 01:03:23,966
but she also wanted to eat it every day.

1696
01:03:24,033 --> 01:03:26,602
However, if you eat
Poong's dish every single day,

1697
01:03:26,669 --> 01:03:28,538
it can cause a stroke.

1698
01:03:28,604 --> 01:03:30,673
What are you talking about?

1699
01:03:30,973 --> 01:03:32,775
THE GEN MZ KID CAME READY TODAY

1700
01:03:32,842 --> 01:03:35,678
I thought of something
that'll go down easily

1701
01:03:35,745 --> 01:03:37,246
and be healthy for you.

1702
01:03:37,313 --> 01:03:39,882
I'll also prepare
soup and sauce on the side

1703
01:03:39,949 --> 01:03:43,052
so you won't get sick of it
even if you have it every day.

1704
01:03:43,886 --> 01:03:45,988
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S INGREDIENTS:
ROMAINE, PERILLA LEAF, SHISHITO PEPPER

1705
01:03:46,055 --> 01:03:48,157
PORK NECK, BRISKET, ENOKI, TOFU,
PEPERONCINO, OYSTER SAUCE, SRIRACHA

1706
01:03:48,224 --> 01:03:50,359
The name of my dish is this.

1707
01:03:50,426 --> 01:03:51,661
Lettuce!

1708
01:03:51,727 --> 01:03:53,462
Set Yourself Together!

1709
01:03:54,764 --> 01:03:56,699
-Lettuce! Set Yourself Together!
-Lettuce! Set Yourself Together!

1710
01:03:56,766 --> 01:03:58,968
-Set yourself.
-Not "Get yourself together."

1711
01:03:59,035 --> 01:04:00,803
What will he make
with the lettuce this time?

1712
01:04:00,870 --> 01:04:03,072
That's a lot.

1713
01:04:03,139 --> 01:04:05,508
-Is lettuce your main ingredient?
-Yes.

1714
01:04:05,575 --> 01:04:06,642
Lettuce

1715
01:04:06,709 --> 01:04:09,312
has always played the supporting role.

1716
01:04:09,378 --> 01:04:10,680
-That's true.
-However,

1717
01:04:10,746 --> 01:04:13,216
it's now time.

1718
01:04:13,282 --> 01:04:16,452
So I'll make a dish
with lettuce as the main ingredient.

1719
01:04:16,519 --> 01:04:18,221
First, lettuce <i>gukbap</i>.

1720
01:04:18,287 --> 01:04:19,956
-What?
-Lettuce <i>gukbap</i>, rice soup?

1721
01:04:20,022 --> 01:04:21,891
-Yes, lettuce <i>gukbap</i>.
-What is that?

1722
01:04:21,958 --> 01:04:24,460
And I'll serve that with lettuce stir-fry.

1723
01:04:24,527 --> 01:04:25,862
-Stir-fry?
-Yes.

1724
01:04:25,928 --> 01:04:28,297
I'll make a Chinese-style
lettuce stir-fry.

1725
01:04:28,364 --> 01:04:29,966
-The lettuce stir-fry.
-Sure.

1726
01:04:30,032 --> 01:04:33,002
-You also seemed to love tea.
-I do.

1727
01:04:33,069 --> 01:04:34,437
I'll use perilla leaves

1728
01:04:34,503 --> 01:04:36,572
to make some tea for you.

1729
01:04:36,639 --> 01:04:37,740
Perilla leaf tea?

1730
01:04:37,807 --> 01:04:38,875
-Yes.
-That's new.

1731
01:04:38,941 --> 01:04:41,611
Why haven't we made tea
with perilla leaves to this day?

1732
01:04:41,677 --> 01:04:43,846
-There's probably a reason.
-Yes, it must be weird.

1733
01:04:43,913 --> 01:04:47,483
Why don't we explore that reason together?

1734
01:04:47,550 --> 01:04:48,751
He's always like this.

1735
01:04:48,818 --> 01:04:51,120
He's good when he faces me,

1736
01:04:51,187 --> 01:04:53,189
but he does weird stuff
with everyone else.

1737
01:04:53,256 --> 01:04:55,758
-So you're making a set meal.
-Yes.

1738
01:04:55,825 --> 01:04:59,795
And now, let us begin the cook-off.

1739
01:04:59,862 --> 01:05:03,499
A doctor among chefs
who can revive one's dying appetite,

1740
01:05:03,566 --> 01:05:05,701
Chef Kwon Sung-jun.

1741
01:05:05,768 --> 01:05:07,870
Versus a hyena who gnaws
on the world of culinary art,

1742
01:05:07,937 --> 01:05:10,339
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong.

1743
01:05:10,406 --> 01:05:13,342
Which one of the two dishes
will surpass hamburgers?

1744
01:05:13,409 --> 01:05:16,846
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1745
01:05:18,147 --> 01:05:19,315
Even with the spotlight,

1746
01:05:19,382 --> 01:05:21,951
Sung-jun's face was not lit up at all.

1747
01:05:22,018 --> 01:05:22,852
Why was it like that?

1748
01:05:22,919 --> 01:05:26,622
It's because his front hair is like this.

1749
01:05:26,689 --> 01:05:29,358
If you grow it out a bit more,
you'll look like Kim Mousse.

1750
01:05:29,926 --> 01:05:31,294
Stop teasing me.

1751
01:05:31,661 --> 01:05:33,663
HIS FRONT FRINGE KEEP GETTING LONGER
WEEK AFTER WEEK

1752
01:05:33,729 --> 01:05:35,932
-Sung-jun cooks meat.
-Meat.

1753
01:05:36,532 --> 01:05:38,401
COOK PASTA

1754
01:05:38,467 --> 01:05:40,236
He's using fettuccine pasta.

1755
01:05:40,603 --> 01:05:41,537
GETS BOILING OIL

1756
01:05:41,604 --> 01:05:44,240
-He's making chili oil.
-He makes chili oil.

1757
01:05:44,307 --> 01:05:46,909
Poong isn't making it, but he is.
Will it turn out nicely?

1758
01:05:46,976 --> 01:05:50,479
Poong has won many stars recently, right?

1759
01:05:50,546 --> 01:05:53,115
Like how some people think
they're a celebrity when they're on TV,

1760
01:05:53,182 --> 01:05:56,185
he now thinks he's a chef
and isn't as funny anymore.

1761
01:05:56,552 --> 01:05:58,587
BORING AND SERIOUS MOVEMENTS

1762
01:05:58,654 --> 01:06:00,823
Why is he cooking so seriously?

1763
01:06:04,126 --> 01:06:05,261
PLAYING TAG WITH GARLIC

1764
01:06:05,328 --> 01:06:06,595
He can't grab the garlic clove.

1765
01:06:06,862 --> 01:06:08,998
WHAT DO YOU MEAN? HE'S STILL FUNNY

1766
01:06:09,065 --> 01:06:10,967
Is that a rubber ball?

1767
01:06:11,033 --> 01:06:13,536
How is that guy in second place right now?

1768
01:06:13,602 --> 01:06:16,639
He has many stars,
but he never gets better at using a knife.

1769
01:06:16,906 --> 01:06:18,374
NEVER GETTING BETTER

1770
01:06:18,441 --> 01:06:20,443
Knife skills have nothing to do
with stars.

1771
01:06:20,509 --> 01:06:22,545
-How does he chop it like that?
-Tell me about it.

1772
01:06:22,611 --> 01:06:24,280
It's like chopping a rice cake bar.

1773
01:06:24,347 --> 01:06:26,882
-You're not supposed to hold it like that.
-You can hurt yourself.

1774
01:06:26,949 --> 01:06:29,418
-The thickness is all different.
-For texture.

1775
01:06:29,485 --> 01:06:30,853
It's to add different textures.

1776
01:06:30,920 --> 01:06:32,188
-Textures.
-Different textures.

1777
01:06:32,555 --> 01:06:33,823
HOW DOES THE ORTHODOX CHEF CHOP?

1778
01:06:34,357 --> 01:06:35,791
QUICK, ACCURATE, AND EVEN!

1779
01:06:37,560 --> 01:06:42,098
2. CHOP ONION AND PORK NECK,
COOK WITH MINCED GARLIC

1780
01:06:42,164 --> 01:06:43,866
Sung-jun begins to cook some meat.

1781
01:06:43,933 --> 01:06:45,668
Are you deep-frying something?

1782
01:06:45,735 --> 01:06:47,837
-I'm frying tofu.
-He's frying tofu.

1783
01:06:47,903 --> 01:06:49,438
Sung-jun's deep-frying tofu.

1784
01:06:49,505 --> 01:06:51,941
-He made long sticks.
-Long sticks?

1785
01:06:52,008 --> 01:06:54,844
-His chili oil is done.
-Yes, the oil.

1786
01:06:54,910 --> 01:06:58,381
Are you using pork neck
as the <i>gimbap</i> filling?

1787
01:06:58,447 --> 01:06:59,949
That's for the pasta.

1788
01:07:00,016 --> 01:07:02,018
Pork neck. He's using lots of meat.

1789
01:07:02,084 --> 01:07:03,486
They're both using pork neck.

1790
01:07:03,552 --> 01:07:06,188
-Poong must be using it too.
-Yes, it's right there.

1791
01:07:06,255 --> 01:07:07,990
Beef brisket.

1792
01:07:08,557 --> 01:07:10,226
Poong uses pork neck.

1793
01:07:10,292 --> 01:07:12,328
He's using beef brisket too.

1794
01:07:12,395 --> 01:07:13,996
-You are?
-Yes.

1795
01:07:14,063 --> 01:07:16,065
-They're using lots of meat.
-It's similar now.

1796
01:07:16,132 --> 01:07:17,466
They're using the same type of meat.

1797
01:07:17,533 --> 01:07:20,069
-What's Poong doing now? <i>Doenjang</i>?
-<i>Doenjang</i>.

1798
01:07:20,136 --> 01:07:21,237
He uses <i>doenjang</i>.

1799
01:07:21,303 --> 01:07:22,304
I'm making <i>gukbap.</i>

1800
01:07:23,005 --> 01:07:24,106
1. ADD RED PEPPER POWDER AND OIL

1801
01:07:24,173 --> 01:07:26,942
He's making meat broth.
Who's going to call that lettuce broth?

1802
01:07:27,009 --> 01:07:28,411
LETTUCE GUKBAP WITHOUT LETTUCE?

1803
01:07:28,477 --> 01:07:30,012
It's just regular meat <i>gukbap</i>.

1804
01:07:30,079 --> 01:07:31,514
Is he using chili oil?

1805
01:07:32,081 --> 01:07:35,718
-It's red pepper powder.
-It's only been four minutes.

1806
01:07:35,785 --> 01:07:37,620
I guess he'll add the lettuce last.

1807
01:07:37,686 --> 01:07:41,357
-That's right. Because it'll get mushy.
-Mushy.

1808
01:07:41,424 --> 01:07:43,959
That's just <i>gukbap</i> with a lettuce topping.

1809
01:07:44,026 --> 01:07:47,029
He's doing that now.

1810
01:07:47,096 --> 01:07:50,132
You're not as charming anymore
now that you're serious.

1811
01:07:50,466 --> 01:07:52,368
SO STRICT ABOUT HIS CHARMS

1812
01:07:52,435 --> 01:07:55,037
He used to respond when we'd tease him.

1813
01:07:55,104 --> 01:07:56,705
-He's focused.
-He thinks he's a chef.

1814
01:07:57,006 --> 01:07:58,841
TRY TO BE FUNNY, WEBTOON ARTIST

1815
01:07:58,908 --> 01:08:00,543
GRANDPA, BE QUIET

1816
01:08:01,243 --> 01:08:02,912
SHRIMP

1817
01:08:03,679 --> 01:08:06,449
Those are the ones I chopped, right?
The bell peppers.

1818
01:08:06,515 --> 01:08:09,018
-Sorry?
-The bell peppers.

1819
01:08:09,085 --> 01:08:12,288
-He got it from your fridge.
-The ones I chopped.

1820
01:08:12,354 --> 01:08:14,924
She points out that she chopped those.

1821
01:08:14,990 --> 01:08:16,592
I knew it. They were so nicely cut.

1822
01:08:16,659 --> 01:08:19,195
-Thank you.
-She's serious about cooking.

1823
01:08:19,261 --> 01:08:20,763
Did you chop them yourself?

1824
01:08:20,830 --> 01:08:23,899
-Yes.
-She loves getting compliments.

1825
01:08:23,966 --> 01:08:25,768
She does. She's really cute.

1826
01:08:25,835 --> 01:08:27,036
-She is.
-The ones she chopped

1827
01:08:27,103 --> 01:08:28,471
are used to make that dish.

1828
01:08:28,537 --> 01:08:30,439
Ye-eun seems proud.

1829
01:08:31,407 --> 01:08:32,641
Oyster sauce.

1830
01:08:32,708 --> 01:08:34,109
Orthodox Chinese.

1831
01:08:34,176 --> 01:08:36,011
-What's he adding now?
-Peanut butter.

1832
01:08:36,078 --> 01:08:39,081
-Peanut butter.
-That's what Poong does.

1833
01:08:39,315 --> 01:08:41,283
IF IT SEEMS LIKE POONG'S STYLE,
YOU'RE MISTAKEN!

1834
01:08:41,917 --> 01:08:43,819
He throws in the pasta.

1835
01:08:43,886 --> 01:08:46,422
FUSION PASTA
IN THE STYLE OF DAN DAN NOODLES

1836
01:08:46,922 --> 01:08:47,756
SESAME OIL

1837
01:08:48,757 --> 01:08:51,393
CHINESE-INSPIRED PASTA, OUT

1838
01:08:51,794 --> 01:08:52,695
WHAT'S POONG UP TO?

1839
01:08:53,129 --> 01:08:56,065
2. ADD GREEN ONION, CRUSHED GARLIC,
AND WATER TO THE MEAT AND MAKE GUKBAP

1840
01:08:56,132 --> 01:08:57,533
What's Poong doing?

1841
01:08:57,600 --> 01:09:00,369
He said he wouldn't make any oil,
but it looks exactly the same!

1842
01:09:00,436 --> 01:09:01,403
It's the same.

1843
01:09:01,470 --> 01:09:03,105
-He just didn't make oil.
-It's chili and oil.

1844
01:09:03,172 --> 01:09:05,508
-The end result looks the same.
-I didn't use chili oil!

1845
01:09:05,574 --> 01:09:08,177
Poong's <i>gukbap</i> always looks like that.

1846
01:09:09,345 --> 01:09:12,448
Should I add enoki later?
Yes, later. That's a better idea.

1847
01:09:12,515 --> 01:09:13,449
Enoki.

1848
01:09:13,516 --> 01:09:14,683
Not yet. No.

1849
01:09:14,750 --> 01:09:17,753
-He'll add it to the <i>gukbap</i> later.
-Later.

1850
01:09:18,053 --> 01:09:20,689
3. MICROWAVE INSTANT RICE

1851
01:09:20,756 --> 01:09:22,024
What do I have to do?

1852
01:09:22,291 --> 01:09:25,928
3. BEAT AN EGG AND COOK IN A PAN

1853
01:09:26,195 --> 01:09:27,263
What's he making?

1854
01:09:27,329 --> 01:09:28,430
Rolled omelet with cheese.

1855
01:09:28,497 --> 01:09:30,199
-Rolled omelet with cheese.
-With string cheese.

1856
01:09:30,266 --> 01:09:32,535
He's rolling string cheese with egg
to use it as a filling.

1857
01:09:32,935 --> 01:09:34,069
DEEP-FRIED TOFU, OUT

1858
01:09:34,136 --> 01:09:36,472
Deep-fried tofu.

1859
01:09:36,539 --> 01:09:37,806
-Carrot.
-Carrot râpées.

1860
01:09:38,974 --> 01:09:42,278
4. MIX JULIENNED CARROT WITH VINEGAR,
MUSTARD, SALT, SUGAR, AND OLIVE OIL

1861
01:09:42,344 --> 01:09:44,580
He's adding vinegar.

1862
01:09:44,647 --> 01:09:47,383
He's seasoning the carrot.

1863
01:09:47,783 --> 01:09:50,619
MIX WELL AND MAKE CARROT RÂPÉES

1864
01:09:51,954 --> 01:09:53,789
STIR-FRY CRUSHED GARLIC IN OIL

1865
01:09:53,856 --> 01:09:55,291
Oyster sauce.

1866
01:09:55,591 --> 01:09:57,560
4. BOIL GARLIC, OYSTER SAUCE,
AND SRIRACHA IN OIL

1867
01:09:57,626 --> 01:09:59,361
Are you making the lettuce stir-fry?

1868
01:09:59,428 --> 01:10:01,263
-Yes, the lettuce stir-fry.
-I see.

1869
01:10:01,330 --> 01:10:03,132
Are you also adding lettuce later?

1870
01:10:03,199 --> 01:10:05,501
Yes, it has to go in later.

1871
01:10:05,568 --> 01:10:08,337
Isn't that so easy? You just need
to add some lettuce at the end.

1872
01:10:08,404 --> 01:10:09,605
Simple, isn't it?

1873
01:10:09,672 --> 01:10:12,908
-But you're adding shishito peppers too.
-Because she had them and likes them.

1874
01:10:12,975 --> 01:10:14,977
-Peperoncino.
-It's not necessary.

1875
01:10:15,044 --> 01:10:16,579
And tofu.

1876
01:10:16,645 --> 01:10:18,781
-Tofu.
-Yes, I need tofu too.

1877
01:10:19,148 --> 01:10:20,149
SWISHING AROUND

1878
01:10:20,216 --> 01:10:22,418
The tofu shapes are uneven too.

1879
01:10:22,484 --> 01:10:26,088
He can't even cut something soft
like tofu into even pieces.

1880
01:10:26,155 --> 01:10:29,725
-The shapes are so uneven.
-It's like handmade tofu.

1881
01:10:29,792 --> 01:10:31,260
How does he chop it like that?

1882
01:10:31,327 --> 01:10:33,128
I do not see any lettuce at the moment.

1883
01:10:33,195 --> 01:10:35,097
He hasn't even started
on the perilla leaf tea.

1884
01:10:35,164 --> 01:10:37,266
-What's that?
-Right. Perilla leaf tea.

1885
01:10:37,333 --> 01:10:39,201
Are you cooking
the perilla leaves right now?

1886
01:10:39,268 --> 01:10:40,970
Yes, I have to roast them.

1887
01:10:41,036 --> 01:10:43,038
He has to make tea with those…

1888
01:10:43,105 --> 01:10:45,107
-By frying it?
-…so he's roasting them without oil.

1889
01:10:45,174 --> 01:10:47,509
He's dry-roasting them without oil.

1890
01:10:47,843 --> 01:10:49,645
WHAT ABOUT SUNG-JUN?

1891
01:10:49,712 --> 01:10:52,147
The egg garnish is too brown.

1892
01:10:52,214 --> 01:10:53,315
-It's an omelet.
-Omelet.

1893
01:10:53,382 --> 01:10:55,784
-It's too brown.
-Isn't it overcooked?

1894
01:10:55,851 --> 01:10:57,486
It's the Maillard reaction.

1895
01:10:57,553 --> 01:11:00,689
-It's not working. It's breaking apart.
-It's torn.

1896
01:11:00,756 --> 01:11:01,790
-It's torn.
-The cheese is spilling out.

1897
01:11:02,091 --> 01:11:03,259
FEELING ANXIOUS…

1898
01:11:03,325 --> 01:11:04,994
So hot.

1899
01:11:05,060 --> 01:11:08,430
He's rolling it like <i>gimbap</i>.
What's that for?

1900
01:11:08,497 --> 01:11:11,200
-I'm trying to shape it.
-It's for the shape.

1901
01:11:11,767 --> 01:11:13,202
You have 6 minutes and 30 seconds.

1902
01:11:13,269 --> 01:11:15,804
-He finally grabs lettuce!
-Lettuce!

1903
01:11:15,871 --> 01:11:19,208
-Those are huge.
-He's using whole leaves?

1904
01:11:19,275 --> 01:11:21,110
Shouldn't you cut them?

1905
01:11:21,176 --> 01:11:22,811
-No, it'll shrivel up.
-I don't think

1906
01:11:22,878 --> 01:11:25,948
even donkeys or rabbits
would eat huge leaves like those.

1907
01:11:26,015 --> 01:11:28,150
It looks like animal feed.

1908
01:11:28,217 --> 01:11:29,685
Even giraffes wouldn't eat that.

1909
01:11:32,221 --> 01:11:33,789
WHY THE FACE?

1910
01:11:33,856 --> 01:11:36,959
-It's not normal lettuce. Is that romaine?
-You're right!

1911
01:11:37,026 --> 01:11:38,460
-That's romaine?
-Yes.

1912
01:11:39,028 --> 01:11:40,095
It looks good.

1913
01:11:40,162 --> 01:11:43,232
You can cook romaine
in heat and even over fire.

1914
01:11:43,299 --> 01:11:44,533
-Really?
-It's shriveling up.

1915
01:11:44,600 --> 01:11:47,536
It'll be like eating
just the top part of bok choy.

1916
01:11:47,603 --> 01:11:49,838
Sung-jun grabs fish cake.

1917
01:11:49,905 --> 01:11:51,540
5. CHOP FISH CAKE INTO LONG PIECES

1918
01:11:52,408 --> 01:11:54,143
AND HE CHOPS SOME MORE!

1919
01:11:54,209 --> 01:11:55,711
He's so fast.

1920
01:11:56,211 --> 01:11:58,213
STIR-FRY WITH FISH CAKE!

1921
01:11:58,280 --> 01:12:00,883
Is that beef bone broth?

1922
01:12:00,949 --> 01:12:01,884
The soup I had.

1923
01:12:01,950 --> 01:12:06,689
He's throwing dumplings in there
to add umami to the soup.

1924
01:12:07,022 --> 01:12:11,393
6. BOIL BROTH WITH GROUND PEPPER,
SALT, SOY SAUCE, SESAME OIL, AND GARLIC

1925
01:12:11,460 --> 01:12:13,429
What's Chef Sung-jun doing with fish cake?

1926
01:12:13,495 --> 01:12:15,130
-I'm making broth.
-Broth?

1927
01:12:15,197 --> 01:12:16,465
Five minutes remaining.

1928
01:12:16,532 --> 01:12:18,701
-Jung-hwan, five minutes!
-I'll report from the scene!

1929
01:12:18,767 --> 01:12:21,070
Okay. Jung-hwan is in action.

1930
01:12:21,136 --> 01:12:22,771
-Sung-jun with two wins in a row.
-Oops.

1931
01:12:23,639 --> 01:12:24,473
Oops.

1932
01:12:24,740 --> 01:12:26,141
THE 2ND PLACE IS SO CLUMSY…

1933
01:12:26,442 --> 01:12:27,910
5. TEAR ENOKI INTO THE GUKBAP

1934
01:12:27,976 --> 01:12:29,912
Can you taste the lettuce <i>gukbap</i>?

1935
01:12:29,978 --> 01:12:31,213
-This thing?
-Yes.

1936
01:12:31,280 --> 01:12:33,182
This still seems too unfinished.

1937
01:12:34,116 --> 01:12:35,984
But you have to let him know.

1938
01:12:36,051 --> 01:12:37,720
I'll try it.

1939
01:12:37,786 --> 01:12:39,455
Poong's lettuce <i>gukbap</i>.

1940
01:12:39,521 --> 01:12:42,091
Will it become a new dish?

1941
01:12:42,157 --> 01:12:43,959
Or will it become a nay dish?

1942
01:12:44,026 --> 01:12:46,161
This one is a nay.

1943
01:12:46,228 --> 01:12:48,130
-So it's a nay?
-So far,

1944
01:12:48,197 --> 01:12:50,299
-it has no flavor.
-No flavor?

1945
01:12:50,366 --> 01:12:53,702
-It'll have to boil some more.
-It's not quite ready yet.

1946
01:12:53,769 --> 01:12:55,537
-He has to cook it some more.
-It's not ready.

1947
01:12:55,604 --> 01:12:57,940
-But there is some umami.
-There is?

1948
01:12:58,540 --> 01:13:01,643
PREPARES HIS SIGNATURE DISH, TILTED RICE

1949
01:13:01,710 --> 01:13:04,680
Mayonnaise and… Is that Sriracha?

1950
01:13:04,747 --> 01:13:07,383
Yes, it's Sriracha, mustard, and wasabi.

1951
01:13:07,449 --> 01:13:09,852
-It's the <i>gimbap</i> dip.
-<i>Gimbap</i> dip?

1952
01:13:09,918 --> 01:13:11,053
What was that last thing?

1953
01:13:11,120 --> 01:13:12,254
-Yogurt.
-It's yogurt.

1954
01:13:12,321 --> 01:13:13,288
It's yogurt.

1955
01:13:13,355 --> 01:13:14,790
Yogurt.

1956
01:13:14,857 --> 01:13:16,859
WHIPS UP THE SAUCE

1957
01:13:17,559 --> 01:13:20,963
7. STRAIN THE BROTH
AND BOIL WITH FISH CAKE STIR-FRY

1958
01:13:21,029 --> 01:13:23,599
As we speak, Sung-jun begins

1959
01:13:23,665 --> 01:13:26,935
-to put pasta on a piece of seaweed.
-He's making pasta <i>gimbap</i>!

1960
01:13:27,002 --> 01:13:28,003
The Chinese-inspired pasta.

1961
01:13:28,070 --> 01:13:30,873
Doesn't he need some empty space
on the seaweed to let it roll up?

1962
01:13:30,939 --> 01:13:34,643
-It has shrimps and pork neck.
-You need some space on the top.

1963
01:13:34,710 --> 01:13:36,412
Okay.

1964
01:13:36,478 --> 01:13:38,680
-Thank you, Master.
-That's perfect.

1965
01:13:38,747 --> 01:13:40,349
He put pasta on it.

1966
01:13:40,416 --> 01:13:41,650
There's a lot of fillings.

1967
01:13:41,717 --> 01:13:44,219
-He's using lettuce too.
-I see.

1968
01:13:44,286 --> 01:13:45,487
This is how you use lettuce.

1969
01:13:45,554 --> 01:13:48,223
-But can you roll it properly?
-I can.

1970
01:13:48,290 --> 01:13:50,559
-Can you really?
-He can always use more seaweed.

1971
01:13:51,460 --> 01:13:52,795
HE GRABS AN EARTHEN POT!

1972
01:13:52,861 --> 01:13:55,230
-Poong prepares an earthen pot.
-He grabs an earthen pot!

1973
01:13:55,297 --> 01:13:56,698
What's he doing now?

1974
01:13:56,765 --> 01:14:00,502
-What's he going to do with it?
-He'll serve the <i>gukbap</i> in it.

1975
01:14:00,569 --> 01:14:03,105
-Served hot.
-Served hot.

1976
01:14:03,172 --> 01:14:04,306
Hot, hot, hot.

1977
01:14:04,373 --> 01:14:06,375
AND HE BRINGS A TEAPOT…

1978
01:14:06,442 --> 01:14:09,278
The tea. He's making the tea.

1979
01:14:09,344 --> 01:14:12,047
-Is he going to pour hot water over it?
-I think so.

1980
01:14:12,714 --> 01:14:14,750
BINGO

1981
01:14:15,451 --> 01:14:17,753
-The perilla leaf tea.
-He's making the tea.

1982
01:14:17,820 --> 01:14:19,688
The perilla leaf tea.

1983
01:14:19,755 --> 01:14:22,624
-He really made tea.
-He really…

1984
01:14:22,691 --> 01:14:25,060
Now, can he really roll it up?

1985
01:14:25,127 --> 01:14:26,495
-It won't work.
-Two sheets?

1986
01:14:26,562 --> 01:14:27,663
Use two sheets.

1987
01:14:27,729 --> 01:14:29,998
-He has to roll this.
-But can he do it?

1988
01:14:30,065 --> 01:14:32,134
This gimbap has too much filling.

1989
01:14:32,201 --> 01:14:33,535
If this were human,

1990
01:14:33,602 --> 01:14:35,971
-it could be Nam-no.
-Really?

1991
01:14:36,038 --> 01:14:37,639
-Two minutes.
-I'm not that thin.

1992
01:14:37,706 --> 01:14:39,174
Isn't that too much?

1993
01:14:39,241 --> 01:14:41,376
Use some pieces of rice. Right here.

1994
01:14:43,946 --> 01:14:45,981
IT'S HARD TO TRUST YOU, SUNG-JUN

1995
01:14:46,048 --> 01:14:48,150
Chef Ho-young,
do you think that'll turn out okay?

1996
01:14:48,984 --> 01:14:50,018
I think it's ruined.

1997
01:14:50,085 --> 01:14:52,387
Ho-young thinks it's ruined.

1998
01:14:52,454 --> 01:14:54,256
The fillings are popping out!

1999
01:14:54,323 --> 01:14:57,326
-It's too thick.
-What's going on? Poong glances over.

2000
01:14:57,392 --> 01:14:58,727
-Yes!
-It's not working!

2001
01:14:58,794 --> 01:15:00,729
EVIL LAUGHTER

2002
01:15:00,963 --> 01:15:03,599
NOISE POLLUTION

2003
01:15:03,665 --> 01:15:04,700
It's perfect.

2004
01:15:04,766 --> 01:15:06,401
-A minute and a half.
-Shouldn't you check?

2005
01:15:06,468 --> 01:15:07,803
A minute and a half.

2006
01:15:07,870 --> 01:15:10,205
Lettuce.

2007
01:15:10,272 --> 01:15:12,875
It looks like Poong might get lucky.

2008
01:15:12,941 --> 01:15:13,809
No way!

2009
01:15:13,876 --> 01:15:16,044
-Sixty seconds!
-Sixty seconds.

2010
01:15:16,111 --> 01:15:19,081
So you'll boil it in the pot
to keep it warm.

2011
01:15:19,147 --> 01:15:22,084
-Warm! So warm!
-Warm! So warm!

2012
01:15:22,684 --> 01:15:24,586
OLD DUDES STARTER PACK: CONSTANT SINGING

2013
01:15:24,887 --> 01:15:26,455
HE'S IMPOSSIBLE…

2014
01:15:26,522 --> 01:15:28,290
-Careful.
-Careful.

2015
01:15:28,557 --> 01:15:31,326
PLATING THE FISH CAKE SOUP

2016
01:15:32,427 --> 01:15:35,063
TIME TO CUT THE GIMBAP

2017
01:15:36,231 --> 01:15:38,000
His <i>gimbap</i>.

2018
01:15:38,066 --> 01:15:40,469
-It's done. His <i>gimbap</i> is done.
-<i>Gimbap</i>!

2019
01:15:40,536 --> 01:15:42,137
I hope he can cut it.
At least it's together.

2020
01:15:42,204 --> 01:15:43,972
The whole thing may pop.

2021
01:15:44,039 --> 01:15:45,240
-Cut it nicely.
-It's the cutting.

2022
01:15:45,307 --> 01:15:46,909
-He's honing the knife.
-Please!

2023
01:15:46,975 --> 01:15:48,243
Sung-jun sharpens the knife!

2024
01:15:48,310 --> 01:15:49,545
I hope it slides in smoothly.

2025
01:15:49,611 --> 01:15:51,046
It has to slide in all the way.

2026
01:15:51,113 --> 01:15:52,614
If it goes wrong, it'll come undone!

2027
01:15:54,883 --> 01:15:55,918
So?

2028
01:15:55,984 --> 01:15:57,619
-The tip was fine.
-It turned out well.

2029
01:15:57,686 --> 01:15:58,954
Is it working?

2030
01:15:59,021 --> 01:16:01,890
-Is it?
-Is it still together?

2031
01:16:01,957 --> 01:16:03,792
-It's together!
-He got one piece!

2032
01:16:03,859 --> 01:16:05,160
-Nice job.
-Not bad.

2033
01:16:05,227 --> 01:16:07,896
-Sung-jun, you have 30 seconds.
-You have 30 seconds.

2034
01:16:07,963 --> 01:16:11,567
-He saved himself. 30 seconds!
-It turned out nicely.

2035
01:16:11,633 --> 01:16:13,669
I thought he'd fail
because he didn't use rice.

2036
01:16:13,735 --> 01:16:14,937
-I thought it'd pop.
-Right?

2037
01:16:15,003 --> 01:16:16,905
-Sung-jun delivers.
-That's Sung-jun.

2038
01:16:16,972 --> 01:16:18,373
Twenty seconds.

2039
01:16:18,440 --> 01:16:21,243
He's serving a whole meal.

2040
01:16:21,310 --> 01:16:24,246
Wait, I think it's popping.
How is it turning out?

2041
01:16:24,313 --> 01:16:25,714
Move it!

2042
01:16:26,848 --> 01:16:29,384
-Ten seconds!
-You have to finish up!

2043
01:16:29,451 --> 01:16:31,286
You can only save a few!

2044
01:16:31,353 --> 01:16:33,322
-The others have popped too.
-Four. Three.

2045
01:16:33,388 --> 01:16:35,223
-Two. One.
-Two. One.

2046
01:16:35,290 --> 01:16:38,727
-Ring the bell! Poong rang it first.
-Poong finishes first.

2047
01:16:38,794 --> 01:16:40,963
HE SERVES THE LETTUCE SET MEAL ON A TRAY

2048
01:16:41,263 --> 01:16:43,398
…WHAT ABOUT HIM?

2049
01:16:43,465 --> 01:16:44,733
Just like that?

2050
01:16:44,800 --> 01:16:45,968
Sung-jun finishes too.

2051
01:16:46,034 --> 01:16:48,537
-Shouldn't he have used some rice?
-That dish

2052
01:16:48,604 --> 01:16:51,473
is made by an orthodox Chinese chef.

2053
01:16:51,540 --> 01:16:52,941
-Looks good.
-"Orthodox."

2054
01:16:53,542 --> 01:16:55,911
You should've listened to Ho-young.

2055
01:16:55,978 --> 01:16:57,579
-I wanted to give him some rice.
-Right?

2056
01:16:57,646 --> 01:16:59,348
You should've used some as glue.

2057
01:16:59,414 --> 01:17:01,149
They're coming.

2058
01:17:01,216 --> 01:17:02,050
TO TAKE HAMBURGERS DOWN!

2059
01:17:02,117 --> 01:17:04,186
-My gosh.
-Both dishes are coming for you.

2060
01:17:04,953 --> 01:17:09,424
And now, everything has been prepared
just for Ye-eun.

2061
01:17:09,491 --> 01:17:11,259
Chef Sung-jun.

2062
01:17:11,326 --> 01:17:14,796
Ho-young kept telling you
to use some rice to keep it together.

2063
01:17:14,863 --> 01:17:17,733
Pasta has more protein and less carbs,

2064
01:17:17,799 --> 01:17:19,768
so I didn't want to use rice for her diet.

2065
01:17:19,835 --> 01:17:21,937
But Nam-no made a rice burger.

2066
01:17:22,004 --> 01:17:24,339
What about Nam-no's rice burger?

2067
01:17:24,406 --> 01:17:26,174
And he used two bowls of rice.

2068
01:17:26,475 --> 01:17:28,176
LIKE THIS!

2069
01:17:28,243 --> 01:17:30,779
Please try
Webtoon Artist Poong's dish first.

2070
01:17:30,846 --> 01:17:32,447
Lettuce! Set Yourself Together!

2071
01:17:32,514 --> 01:17:36,551
A MEAL WITH LETTUCE AS ITS MAIN INGREDIENT

2072
01:17:37,319 --> 01:17:38,520
PERILLA LEAF TEA

2073
01:17:40,422 --> 01:17:44,660
LETTUCE GUKBAP WITH PLENTY OF LETTUCE

2074
01:17:45,794 --> 01:17:49,064
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S
LETTUCE! SET YOURSELF TOGETHER!

2075
01:17:49,131 --> 01:17:51,867
-How do I eat this?
-First of all,

2076
01:17:51,933 --> 01:17:53,902
please try some perilla leaf tea.

2077
01:17:53,969 --> 01:17:55,637
Can she try that later?

2078
01:17:55,704 --> 01:17:57,706
Does she have to drink the tea first?

2079
01:17:58,473 --> 01:18:00,342
You can have it later.

2080
01:18:00,409 --> 01:18:04,046
I mean, she might
completely lose her appetite after that.

2081
01:18:04,112 --> 01:18:06,214
Let's push that back to the end.

2082
01:18:06,281 --> 01:18:07,315
Oh, wait.

2083
01:18:07,382 --> 01:18:09,051
Come to think of it, try the tea first.

2084
01:18:09,117 --> 01:18:11,420
-It has a subtle smell.
-Because the aroma

2085
01:18:11,486 --> 01:18:14,389
isn't too strong, but quite subtle.

2086
01:18:14,456 --> 01:18:16,958
It can help calm you down.

2087
01:18:17,025 --> 01:18:18,960
You can make tea with perilla leaves?

2088
01:18:19,027 --> 01:18:21,396
-I didn't know.
-It's my first time.

2089
01:18:22,030 --> 01:18:25,200
After all, Ye-eun loves Korean food,

2090
01:18:25,267 --> 01:18:28,036
so I think she might like it.

2091
01:18:28,103 --> 01:18:29,171
Welcome tea.

2092
01:18:29,237 --> 01:18:30,405
What's perilla leaf tea like?

2093
01:18:32,808 --> 01:18:33,909
MMM

2094
01:18:33,975 --> 01:18:37,813
It has the characteristic
of tea that I like.

2095
01:18:37,879 --> 01:18:40,949
I like tea that does not have any taste,

2096
01:18:41,016 --> 01:18:43,618
because I only enjoy the subtle scent

2097
01:18:43,685 --> 01:18:46,321
that hits me right before I sip on it.

2098
01:18:46,388 --> 01:18:48,690
-Perilla leaf tea was a success.
-Yes.

2099
01:18:48,757 --> 01:18:49,991
Please try the <i>gukbap</i>.

2100
01:18:50,058 --> 01:18:52,928
There are a lot of ingredients in here.

2101
01:18:52,994 --> 01:18:55,564
That's <i>gukbap</i> served with the rice
on the side, so feel free to mix it in.

2102
01:18:55,630 --> 01:18:56,965
Please enjoy it as you like.

2103
01:18:57,032 --> 01:18:58,934
She's not good with something too hot.

2104
01:18:59,601 --> 01:19:01,002
Lettuce <i>gukbap</i>.

2105
01:19:01,069 --> 01:19:03,638
She tries the soup first.
I hope she likes it.

2106
01:19:03,705 --> 01:19:05,373
Whoa. This is good.

2107
01:19:05,440 --> 01:19:07,109
It's good?

2108
01:19:09,211 --> 01:19:10,846
He didn't even make chili oil today.

2109
01:19:10,912 --> 01:19:12,481
Let me try the lettuce.

2110
01:19:13,048 --> 01:19:15,517
She found a lump of lettuce.

2111
01:19:16,084 --> 01:19:18,653
A BIG BITE OF LETTUCE

2112
01:19:18,720 --> 01:19:22,090
I wonder what lettuce <i>gukbap</i> is like.

2113
01:19:22,157 --> 01:19:23,391
MMM

2114
01:19:23,458 --> 01:19:26,628
I've seen <i>gukbap </i>with <i>ugeoji</i>, which is
dried napa cabbage leaves, or even mallow.

2115
01:19:26,695 --> 01:19:29,197
-It reminds me of dried napa cabbage.
-Like <i>ugeoji?</i>

2116
01:19:29,831 --> 01:19:31,166
BUT CRUNCHIER THAN UGEOJI

2117
01:19:31,233 --> 01:19:33,635
It's fresher than <i>ugeoji.</i>

2118
01:19:33,702 --> 01:19:35,570
I don't drink,

2119
01:19:35,637 --> 01:19:37,839
but it feels like
this is curing my hangover.

2120
01:19:37,906 --> 01:19:39,274
-You can feel it?
-Yes.

2121
01:19:39,341 --> 01:19:42,911
It feels like it's getting rid
of all my hangovers.

2122
01:19:42,978 --> 01:19:45,413
You don't drink,
yet you know what it feels like?

2123
01:19:45,480 --> 01:19:46,314
She does drink.

2124
01:19:46,381 --> 01:19:49,551
HOW DO YOU KNOW THAT FEELING?

2125
01:19:49,618 --> 01:19:51,820
She knows that feeling
when it all melts away.

2126
01:19:51,887 --> 01:19:53,588
It feels like everything is clearing up.

2127
01:19:53,655 --> 01:19:55,857
You do drink. You drink a lot.

2128
01:19:55,924 --> 01:19:57,959
-She knows that hangover feel.
-She drinks a lot.

2129
01:19:58,026 --> 01:20:01,696
-Hangover cures clear your insides.
-She can still feel it.

2130
01:20:01,763 --> 01:20:02,697
So she drinks.

2131
01:20:02,764 --> 01:20:04,666
-Does it taste rich?
-It does.

2132
01:20:04,733 --> 01:20:06,301
I can taste

2133
01:20:06,368 --> 01:20:09,137
the rich flavor of the meat.

2134
01:20:09,538 --> 01:20:11,907
ANOTHER MOUTHFUL

2135
01:20:12,274 --> 01:20:13,575
PLEASED

2136
01:20:13,642 --> 01:20:14,609
Look at her eat.

2137
01:20:14,676 --> 01:20:16,978
MMM MMM MMMM?
(HOW DO I EAT THIS?)

2138
01:20:17,045 --> 01:20:19,080
-Have it with rice.
-With rice?

2139
01:20:19,147 --> 01:20:20,949
Top it over rice

2140
01:20:21,016 --> 01:20:23,151
-and have them together. You'll like it.
-It must be good.

2141
01:20:23,218 --> 01:20:25,353
Something must be
wrong with me today, Eun-yeong.

2142
01:20:25,420 --> 01:20:27,789
I ate so much in the green room,
yet why am I still hungry?

2143
01:20:27,856 --> 01:20:29,524
You're always like that.

2144
01:20:29,925 --> 01:20:32,861
A BITE OF RICE AND LETTUCE STIR-FRY

2145
01:20:37,833 --> 01:20:39,100
It tastes just like that.

2146
01:20:39,167 --> 01:20:41,169
What's that Chinese dish called?

2147
01:20:41,236 --> 01:20:42,571
Morning glory stir-fry?

2148
01:20:42,637 --> 01:20:44,840
-Yes, it tastes just like that.
-You're right.

2149
01:20:44,906 --> 01:20:47,042
It's similar to that dish.

2150
01:20:47,108 --> 01:20:48,510
-Was it intentional?
-It was.

2151
01:20:48,577 --> 01:20:50,912
But you seemed to like spicy food,

2152
01:20:50,979 --> 01:20:52,781
so I added a little bit of Sriracha.

2153
01:20:52,848 --> 01:20:56,218
You can create a similar texture
by using lettuce.

2154
01:20:56,284 --> 01:20:59,187
I like how I can eat this,
and then freshen my palate

2155
01:20:59,254 --> 01:21:01,389
-with this tea.
-You're right.

2156
01:21:01,456 --> 01:21:03,425
That tea was made with perilla leaves,

2157
01:21:03,491 --> 01:21:05,193
and it's clearer than I expected.

2158
01:21:05,260 --> 01:21:07,696
-It's good. It's really good.
-She says it's good.

2159
01:21:07,762 --> 01:21:11,099
Next, Chef Sung-jun's dish,
Doctor on the Matfia.

2160
01:21:11,566 --> 01:21:15,403
A CLASSIC COMBINATION
OF FISH CAKE SOUP AND GIMBAP

2161
01:21:16,371 --> 01:21:20,675
GIMBAP MADE WITH CHINESE-INSPIRED PASTA
INSTEAD OF RICE

2162
01:21:21,877 --> 01:21:26,081
CHEF KWON SUNG-JUN'S DOCTOR ON THE MATFIA

2163
01:21:26,147 --> 01:21:28,049
First, try a sip of the soup

2164
01:21:28,116 --> 01:21:30,485
and wash down whatever Poong made.

2165
01:21:32,053 --> 01:21:34,856
-Is that regular fish cake soup?
-I made the soup

2166
01:21:34,923 --> 01:21:37,192
by adding dumplings in the broth,

2167
01:21:37,259 --> 01:21:39,261
as well as onion and fish cake.

2168
01:21:39,327 --> 01:21:42,397
This will compare to Poong's <i>gukbap</i>.

2169
01:21:42,464 --> 01:21:43,999
It'll taste light.

2170
01:21:44,866 --> 01:21:46,167
MMM

2171
01:21:46,234 --> 01:21:47,369
IMMEDIATELY AMAZED

2172
01:21:47,435 --> 01:21:51,273
It's different
from any fish cake soup I've had,

2173
01:21:51,339 --> 01:21:52,173
and it's delicious.

2174
01:21:52,240 --> 01:21:55,310
It sticks to my mouth,
and then it disappears.

2175
01:21:55,377 --> 01:21:56,511
Nothing stands out.

2176
01:21:56,578 --> 01:21:57,512
No.

2177
01:21:57,779 --> 01:21:58,780
JUST AS YOU LIKE

2178
01:21:58,847 --> 01:22:00,582
He tried not to let anything stand out.

2179
01:22:00,649 --> 01:22:02,684
Next, the <i>gimbap</i>. It's pasta <i>gimbap</i>.

2180
01:22:02,751 --> 01:22:03,752
Do I just eat it as is?

2181
01:22:03,818 --> 01:22:06,488
-Try the sauce later.
-First, just the <i>gimbap</i>.

2182
01:22:06,554 --> 01:22:07,622
It's too big.

2183
01:22:08,290 --> 01:22:10,725
-It looks huge.
-I knew she'd do it.

2184
01:22:11,293 --> 01:22:14,663
Ye-eun really loves <i>gimbap</i>.

2185
01:22:14,729 --> 01:22:17,299
He made it with pasta, not rice.

2186
01:22:17,365 --> 01:22:20,669
-I used almost a dozen ingredients.
-Shrimp, pork neck, brisket,

2187
01:22:20,735 --> 01:22:21,603
-Lettuce.
-lettuce…

2188
01:22:21,670 --> 01:22:24,539
Carrot <i>râpées</i>, pasta,
many different sauces,

2189
01:22:24,606 --> 01:22:25,941
-and deep-fried tofu.
-Yes, tofu.

2190
01:22:26,007 --> 01:22:27,008
But nothing will stand out.

2191
01:22:27,075 --> 01:22:28,910
MM, MMMM MMMMM
(FRIED TOFU! YES, YOU'RE RIGHT)

2192
01:22:28,977 --> 01:22:30,412
What are you saying?

2193
01:22:30,478 --> 01:22:34,249
-She likes to have her mouth full.
-Yes, that's it.

2194
01:22:34,316 --> 01:22:35,984
It's a taste that makes you happy.

2195
01:22:36,051 --> 01:22:37,719
-Really?
-Yes.

2196
01:22:37,786 --> 01:22:39,988
So pasta-filled <i>gimbap…</i>

2197
01:22:40,055 --> 01:22:42,023
-Nice.
-…can make you happy too.

2198
01:22:42,090 --> 01:22:44,693
-It's pretty big, though.
-It doesn't feel like it's missing rice.

2199
01:22:44,759 --> 01:22:46,528
-Really?
-How could that be possible?

2200
01:22:46,594 --> 01:22:48,096
It tastes like it's there.

2201
01:22:48,163 --> 01:22:51,800
The mix of peanut butter, tofu, and pasta

2202
01:22:51,866 --> 01:22:55,103
can give a similar texture to rice.

2203
01:22:55,170 --> 01:22:59,074
He didn't use rice,
but it feels like she's eating rice.

2204
01:22:59,140 --> 01:23:01,576
-Why don't you try it with the sauce?
-Yes, try the sauce.

2205
01:23:01,643 --> 01:23:05,847
-I like to eat <i>gimbap</i> with wasabi, so…
-That piece is so big.

2206
01:23:05,914 --> 01:23:06,881
You know what's good.

2207
01:23:06,948 --> 01:23:08,583
I knew you'd like it too.

2208
01:23:08,850 --> 01:23:10,652
PERFECT HARMONY

2209
01:23:10,719 --> 01:23:13,521
-That <i>gimbap</i> is huge.
-It's really big.

2210
01:23:17,392 --> 01:23:19,961
Goodness. She eats it all in one bite.

2211
01:23:20,028 --> 01:23:23,398
She likes food that gives her
many different flavors at once.

2212
01:23:23,465 --> 01:23:25,467
Your mouth seems small,
but it's big inside.

2213
01:23:25,533 --> 01:23:27,535
-You're right.
-That's true.

2214
01:23:27,602 --> 01:23:29,671
-Her mouth must be big inside.
-Whoa. That huge thing fit inside.

2215
01:23:29,738 --> 01:23:31,806
When it feels too dry,
have a sip of the soup.

2216
01:23:31,873 --> 01:23:33,208
Then you can continue to eat.

2217
01:23:33,274 --> 01:23:35,810
You're really talkative today.

2218
01:23:35,877 --> 01:23:37,679
I'm always talkative.

2219
01:23:37,746 --> 01:23:39,247
Try some soup.

2220
01:23:39,314 --> 01:23:41,449
WHEN IT FEELS DRY, HAVE FISH CAKE SOUP

2221
01:23:42,717 --> 01:23:45,920
That's it. You do need some soup
when you eat <i>gimbap</i>.

2222
01:23:45,987 --> 01:23:46,821
That's right.

2223
01:23:46,888 --> 01:23:48,656
I want to chug this.

2224
01:23:49,491 --> 01:23:51,059
Did you drink last night?

2225
01:23:51,126 --> 01:23:53,061
-She did. She drank.
-She did.

2226
01:23:53,128 --> 01:23:55,397
-She drank yesterday too.
-Until midnight.

2227
01:23:55,463 --> 01:23:58,266
We had an early day,
so she went home right at midnight.

2228
01:23:59,401 --> 01:24:00,835
APPLAUSE OF SATISFACTION

2229
01:24:00,902 --> 01:24:03,004
-This was delicious.
-That sounds great.

2230
01:24:03,071 --> 01:24:06,674
Now, let's try Poong's dish first.

2231
01:24:07,942 --> 01:24:08,777
I'm curious.

2232
01:24:08,843 --> 01:24:11,613
Hey, this really turned into tea.

2233
01:24:12,380 --> 01:24:14,382
-It's like dried perilla seeds.
-It is.

2234
01:24:14,449 --> 01:24:16,985
-It smells like perilla seeds.
-Or perilla oil.

2235
01:24:17,052 --> 01:24:18,286
How did he come up with this?

2236
01:24:18,353 --> 01:24:21,056
When I tried it out there,
it was still a bit bland.

2237
01:24:22,490 --> 01:24:24,292
-Mmm.
-It's much richer now.

2238
01:24:24,359 --> 01:24:25,960
This is almost like cheating.

2239
01:24:26,327 --> 01:24:28,063
PICKING UP A HUGE PIECE

2240
01:24:28,296 --> 01:24:30,565
EATING THE WHOLE THING

2241
01:24:30,632 --> 01:24:34,269
IT OPENED UP JUN-YOUNG'S APPETITE

2242
01:24:34,636 --> 01:24:36,538
AND

2243
01:24:37,072 --> 01:24:38,706
THE GUY WHOSE APPETITE IS ALWAYS OPEN

2244
01:24:38,773 --> 01:24:39,841
This is just <i>gukbap</i>.

2245
01:24:39,908 --> 01:24:41,676
Nam-no, are you already done?

2246
01:24:41,743 --> 01:24:43,745
-I finished two bowls.
-What's your take?

2247
01:24:43,812 --> 01:24:47,482
There's something called <i>doenjang sulbap</i>,
a delicious <i>gukbap</i> from barbecue places.

2248
01:24:47,549 --> 01:24:50,518
It tastes like that,
but with lots of lettuce.

2249
01:24:50,585 --> 01:24:52,687
There's that green aroma,

2250
01:24:52,754 --> 01:24:54,322
which acts like water parsley.

2251
01:24:54,389 --> 01:24:55,757
-The lettuce?
-Yes.

2252
01:24:55,824 --> 01:24:57,759
I want to ask Jun-young,

2253
01:24:57,826 --> 01:24:59,828
but he's enjoying it a bit too much.

2254
01:24:59,894 --> 01:25:02,030
He has to eat more later.

2255
01:25:02,097 --> 01:25:05,567
This soup doesn't taste like
something Poong made.

2256
01:25:05,633 --> 01:25:07,802
It's like the kind of soup

2257
01:25:07,869 --> 01:25:11,106
a grandma simmered for a long time
with high-quality <i>doenjang</i>.

2258
01:25:11,172 --> 01:25:12,107
-Are you done, Jun-young?
-Yes.

2259
01:25:12,173 --> 01:25:13,007
Any thoughts?

2260
01:25:13,074 --> 01:25:15,043
It was really delicious.

2261
01:25:15,110 --> 01:25:18,480
I want to try making this at home.

2262
01:25:19,047 --> 01:25:21,116
-It tastes like a hearty soup.
-I see.

2263
01:25:21,182 --> 01:25:23,985
-That was delicious.
-All right.

2264
01:25:24,052 --> 01:25:25,987
This <i>gukbap</i> was good,

2265
01:25:26,054 --> 01:25:27,288
but it was the tea for me.

2266
01:25:27,355 --> 01:25:29,858
When I was a kid,
I'd go to my grandma's place

2267
01:25:29,924 --> 01:25:32,026
and play hide-and-seek there.

2268
01:25:32,093 --> 01:25:33,528
I often hid in the perilla field.

2269
01:25:33,595 --> 01:25:35,897
So as a kid…

2270
01:25:35,964 --> 01:25:38,099
Perilla plants aren't that tall.

2271
01:25:38,166 --> 01:25:40,034
-I was still a kid.
-As a kid.

2272
01:25:40,101 --> 01:25:43,671
Anyway, it felt like my childhood,
and when I opened my eyes,

2273
01:25:43,738 --> 01:25:45,273
it was as if I were at a green tea farm.

2274
01:25:45,673 --> 01:25:48,276
AMAZED

2275
01:25:48,343 --> 01:25:51,412
He brings up his old memories and talks
so much, now that he's in first place.

2276
01:25:51,479 --> 01:25:54,415
-I almost cried.
-That was a beautiful expression.

2277
01:25:54,482 --> 01:25:56,050
He opened his eyes at a green tea field.

2278
01:25:56,117 --> 01:25:58,853
-No one's that expressive.
-Yes, that was fantastic.

2279
01:25:58,920 --> 01:25:59,988
A blatant lie.

2280
01:26:01,189 --> 01:26:02,657
Next up,

2281
01:26:02,724 --> 01:26:04,893
Chef Sung-jun's dish.

2282
01:26:04,959 --> 01:26:06,394
Doctor on the Matfia.

2283
01:26:07,362 --> 01:26:08,696
2ND YUM

2284
01:26:08,930 --> 01:26:10,298
3RD YUM

2285
01:26:12,200 --> 01:26:14,369
SLURP

2286
01:26:14,936 --> 01:26:16,871
What's Nam-no eating?

2287
01:26:16,938 --> 01:26:18,840
Oh, he's eating the pasta.

2288
01:26:19,207 --> 01:26:22,310
SUCKED INTO HIS MUKBANG LIKE THAT PASTA

2289
01:26:22,377 --> 01:26:25,446
That's how he gets paid.

2290
01:26:26,414 --> 01:26:28,483
At times, it's the production's loss.

2291
01:26:28,550 --> 01:26:30,018
It's still a loss for us.

2292
01:26:33,321 --> 01:26:37,358
I was looking forward
to trying this pasta.

2293
01:26:37,425 --> 01:26:39,194
If he didn't say this was pasta,

2294
01:26:39,260 --> 01:26:43,498
I would've thought this was
nicely seasoned fish cake.

2295
01:26:43,565 --> 01:26:45,833
I think Sung-jun planned everything.

2296
01:26:46,401 --> 01:26:49,037
Jong-won, no hide-and-seek for this one?

2297
01:26:49,103 --> 01:26:51,105
I know what exactly this is.

2298
01:26:51,172 --> 01:26:52,140
-Yes?
-Where did you hide?

2299
01:26:52,207 --> 01:26:53,141
Well…

2300
01:26:53,474 --> 01:26:56,211
DO YOU HAVE TO HIDE SOMEWHERE BY DEFAULT?

2301
01:26:56,277 --> 01:26:59,714
When I work at the restaurant
near Gangnam Station,

2302
01:26:59,781 --> 01:27:03,218
there was a huge lunch fad
around keto <i>gimbap,</i>

2303
01:27:03,284 --> 01:27:04,619
which is made without rice.

2304
01:27:04,686 --> 01:27:07,255
It tastes like a well-balanced keto <i>gimbap</i>

2305
01:27:07,322 --> 01:27:09,023
made with good ingredients.

2306
01:27:09,090 --> 01:27:11,292
It feels like I'm hiding in Gangnam.

2307
01:27:11,359 --> 01:27:14,028
<i>Hiding in Gangnam. All right.</i>

2308
01:27:14,095 --> 01:27:16,164
Very well then. It's time to choose again.

2309
01:27:16,231 --> 01:27:19,701
There was a lot of planning
and analysis going on in this round.

2310
01:27:19,767 --> 01:27:22,604
Which one will the fridge owner choose?

2311
01:27:22,670 --> 01:27:24,138
<i>Press one for Kwon Sung-jun,</i>

2312
01:27:25,006 --> 01:27:26,374
<i>and two for Kim Poong.</i>

2313
01:27:27,342 --> 01:27:28,676
Please make your choice

2314
01:27:28,743 --> 01:27:30,545
and press the button!

2315
01:27:31,279 --> 01:27:32,213
I did.

2316
01:27:32,280 --> 01:27:33,248
Already?

2317
01:27:33,314 --> 01:27:35,650
-Was it an easy decision?
-No.

2318
01:27:35,717 --> 01:27:37,151
You told me

2319
01:27:37,218 --> 01:27:39,287
-to press it, so I did.
-Is that so? Very good.

2320
01:27:39,354 --> 01:27:42,323
Let's find out the result. Show us!

2321
01:27:42,390 --> 01:27:44,759
This was their first round this year.

2322
01:27:44,826 --> 01:27:48,029
Poong and Sung-jun
already know too much about each other.

2323
01:27:48,096 --> 01:27:49,764
Which dish

2324
01:27:49,831 --> 01:27:51,132
did Ye-eun choose?

2325
01:27:51,199 --> 01:27:53,334
An addictive new dish!

2326
01:27:53,401 --> 01:27:54,535
Which one was that?

2327
01:27:55,403 --> 01:27:57,438
Show us!

2328
01:27:57,505 --> 01:27:58,740
KWON SUNG-JUN WINS

2329
01:27:58,806 --> 01:28:00,141
Kwon Sung-jun wins!

2330
01:28:00,208 --> 01:28:02,777
CHEF KWON SUNG-JUN'S
DOCTOR ON THE MATFIA WINS

2331
01:28:02,844 --> 01:28:03,911
Kwon Sung-jun wins!

2332
01:28:03,978 --> 01:28:06,314
3 WINS IN A ROW
HE'S BEEN ON A ROLL LATELY

2333
01:28:06,814 --> 01:28:10,318
He captured Ye-eun's heart.

2334
01:28:10,385 --> 01:28:12,587
The moment I put the <i>gimbap</i> in my mouth,

2335
01:28:13,187 --> 01:28:15,923
it felt like I was dropped in a maze.

2336
01:28:15,990 --> 01:28:16,824
A MAZE?

2337
01:28:16,891 --> 01:28:19,093
"Is this it? Oh, no."

2338
01:28:19,160 --> 01:28:20,695
"Is this it? No."

2339
01:28:20,762 --> 01:28:22,363
Although I was lost,

2340
01:28:22,430 --> 01:28:24,399
but I was happy to be lost.

2341
01:28:24,465 --> 01:28:25,733
And so,

2342
01:28:25,800 --> 01:28:28,970
I thought, "Is this shrimp?
Is this tofu? Is this pasta?"

2343
01:28:29,037 --> 01:28:31,839
I loved the balance as I got to enjoy
and savor every single flavor.

2344
01:28:31,906 --> 01:28:33,741
It made me so happy.

2345
01:28:35,043 --> 01:28:39,147
So she played hide-and-seek with Sung-jun.

2346
01:28:39,213 --> 01:28:42,317
-They played tag.
-That was why I chose him.

2347
01:28:42,383 --> 01:28:43,651
Nice job.

2348
01:28:43,718 --> 01:28:45,887
-Poong, it's a shame.
-What a shame.

2349
01:28:45,953 --> 01:28:47,855
It's all right. Because today,

2350
01:28:47,922 --> 01:28:49,390
I got to learn some things.

2351
01:28:49,457 --> 01:28:50,958
I realized

2352
01:28:51,025 --> 01:28:54,829
perilla leaves and lettuce
could also be great main ingredients.

2353
01:28:54,896 --> 01:28:58,333
-It was a great lesson for me.
-Is that so?

2354
01:28:58,399 --> 01:29:00,335
Why do you talk like an actual chef?

2355
01:29:00,401 --> 01:29:02,737
What about the variety show aspect?

2356
01:29:02,804 --> 01:29:04,539
He's boring and less charming.

2357
01:29:05,106 --> 01:29:07,241
We can't have you keep doing this.

2358
01:29:07,975 --> 01:29:08,843
You're less charming.

2359
01:29:08,910 --> 01:29:10,311
This is so unfair!

2360
01:29:10,378 --> 01:29:12,480
-I should've won!
-That's what I'm talking about!

2361
01:29:13,281 --> 01:29:14,449
SURPRISED

2362
01:29:14,515 --> 01:29:16,417
-I should've won!
-That's what I'm talking about!

2363
01:29:16,484 --> 01:29:19,821
-That's your job.
-I'll get my revenge, Ye-eun!

2364
01:29:20,188 --> 01:29:21,222
OKAY, CUT!

2365
01:29:21,289 --> 01:29:22,657
He'll get his revenge!

2366
01:29:22,724 --> 01:29:24,992
Kwon Sung-jun
is the winner of this cook-off!

2367
01:29:25,059 --> 01:29:26,527
Please put a star on him!

2368
01:29:27,195 --> 01:29:30,131
I was the opposite.
I thought you'd win. It was so good.

2369
01:29:30,365 --> 01:29:32,200
A WARM CONSOLATION

2370
01:29:32,266 --> 01:29:36,204
Sung-jun now has four stars.

2371
01:29:36,270 --> 01:29:37,572
Congratulations, Sung-jun!

2372
01:29:37,638 --> 01:29:38,873
NICE JOB

2373
01:29:39,774 --> 01:29:42,477
Jun-young is known to be a good cook.

2374
01:29:42,543 --> 01:29:44,512
I often make my own food at home.

2375
01:29:44,579 --> 01:29:46,781
We present Jun-young's fridge!

2376
01:29:46,848 --> 01:29:48,249
-Hey, what?
-Whoa.

2377
01:29:48,316 --> 01:29:49,751
You staged that, didn't you?

2378
01:29:49,817 --> 01:29:51,252
<i>Look at how organized he is.</i>

2379
01:29:51,319 --> 01:29:52,487
<i>He labeled everything.</i>

2380
01:29:52,553 --> 01:29:53,955
I'm feeling quite at ease.

2381
01:29:55,256 --> 01:29:57,091
He loves ramen very much.

2382
01:29:57,158 --> 01:29:58,726
Why do you have things in bulk?

2383
01:29:58,793 --> 01:29:59,827
It's mostly for broth.

2384
01:29:59,894 --> 01:30:01,729
-You have lots of meat.
-I use it to make <i>chashu</i>.

2385
01:30:01,796 --> 01:30:02,830
You make it at home?

2386
01:30:02,897 --> 01:30:03,898
When I was hooked,

2387
01:30:03,965 --> 01:30:07,168
I used to boil the broth
for 48 hours straight.

2388
01:30:07,235 --> 01:30:09,771
A ramen cook-off just for Jun-young!

2389
01:30:09,837 --> 01:30:11,105
That broth is everything.

2390
01:30:11,172 --> 01:30:12,440
<i>Chashu!</i>

2391
01:30:12,507 --> 01:30:13,708
I want to try that.

2392
01:30:13,775 --> 01:30:14,809
He took a bite.

2393
01:30:15,176 --> 01:30:16,477
BURYING HIS FACE IN THE BOWL

2394
01:30:17,645 --> 01:30:19,013
It's so good.

2395
01:30:19,080 --> 01:30:20,548
The first body swap round

2396
01:30:20,615 --> 01:30:21,883
here at <i>Chef & My Fridge!</i>

2397
01:30:21,949 --> 01:30:24,152
-He's good with a Chinese knife.
-He's like a Chinese chef.

2398
01:30:24,218 --> 01:30:25,286
They swapped bodies.

2399
01:30:25,353 --> 01:30:27,922
-I'm in that French vibe.
-That's a French technique.

2400
01:30:27,989 --> 01:30:29,490
Wait, that's Chinese!

2401
01:30:29,557 --> 01:30:30,992
You don't use high heat in French!

2402
01:30:31,058 --> 01:30:32,293
<i>Bonjour.</i>

2403
01:30:32,527 --> 01:30:33,561
A PARISIENNE AT HEART

2404
01:30:33,628 --> 01:30:34,762
<i>Merci beaucoup.</i>

2405
01:30:34,829 --> 01:30:35,830
Does it taste French?

2406
01:30:35,897 --> 01:30:37,198
<i>Da jia hao.</i>

2407
01:30:37,265 --> 01:30:38,433
THE VIBE KEEPS TURNING STRANGE

2408
01:30:38,499 --> 01:30:41,068
-My dish is called…
-Called?

2409
01:30:41,135 --> 01:30:42,203
Park Eun-yeong.

2410
01:30:44,639 --> 01:30:45,840
DID THEY ACTUALLY SWAP BODIES?

2411
01:30:45,907 --> 01:30:46,874
Great job!

2412
01:30:46,941 --> 01:30:48,976
WILL JONG-WON DO SOMETHING
OUT OF CHARACTER?

2413
01:30:49,043 --> 01:30:51,446
